  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3323807647" />
    <a title="Bryan Alkire" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/72479728-bryan-alkire"><img alt="Bryan Alkire" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1613140523p2/72479728.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3323807647?book_show_action=true">May 10, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bryan Alkire" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bryan Alkire" href="/user/show/72479728-bryan-alkire">Bryan Alkire</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3323807647" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6919477831144426775">Excellent book. Certainly, puts the current situation into perspective. It really brings to mind the proverb that there’s nothing so bad that it couldn’t get worse. That aptly describes the corner of the Dustbowl this book focuses on. The writing is readable and compelling at times. The book is well organized though some people seemed to get more time at the expense of others. The contents are heart ranching at times and it helped to read with a beer at hand to soften the hard edge of the povert</span>
  <span id="freeText6919477831144426775" style="display:none">Excellent book. Certainly, puts the current situation into perspective. It really brings to mind the proverb that there’s nothing so bad that it couldn’t get worse. That aptly describes the corner of the Dustbowl this book focuses on. The writing is readable and compelling at times. The book is well organized though some people seemed to get more time at the expense of others. The contents are heart ranching at times and it helped to read with a beer at hand to soften the hard edge of the poverty in the book. It made me realize more just how lucky we are in the current crisis…as bad as it is, it could be much worse. That said, I do realize that the two aren’t really analogous, it’s tough to compare rural nowhere small homesteads on marginal land in the 1930’s to urbanized America of 2020…but there are parallels to a certain degree nonetheless and this book draws them out in a good way. <br /> <br />So, I give this a 5. It’s effecting, compelling and made me think. It’s hard to ask much more from a book…<br /> </span>
  <a data-text-id="6919477831144426775" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


