  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3480928224" />
    <a title="Stephanie Anze" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/27117957-stephanie-anze"><img alt="Stephanie Anze" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1604709893p2/27117957.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3480928224?book_show_action=true">Aug 20, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Stephanie Anze" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Stephanie Anze" href="/user/show/27117957-stephanie-anze">Stephanie Anze</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/6556577-the-worst-hard-time">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/27117957-stephanie-anze?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/27117957-stephanie-anze?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3480928224" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16988560157866833959">“Of all the countries in the world, we Americans have been the greatest destroyers of land of any race of people barbaric or civilized,&quot; Bennett said in a speech at the start of the dust storms. What was happening, he said, was &quot;sinister&quot;, a symptom of &quot;our stupendous ignorance.” <br/><br/>Five stars for a striking book about a history that almost appears to be forgotten!<br/><br/>As farmers and settlers come to the High Plains to make their homes and raise their families, they are not aware about the hard times th</span>
  <span id="freeText16988560157866833959" style="display:none">“Of all the countries in the world, we Americans have been the greatest destroyers of land of any race of people barbaric or civilized," Bennett said in a speech at the start of the dust storms. What was happening, he said, was "sinister", a symptom of "our stupendous ignorance.” <br /><br />Five stars for a striking book about a history that almost appears to be forgotten!<br /><br />As farmers and settlers come to the High Plains to make their homes and raise their families, they are not aware about the hard times they are going to come up against. They work and over-plow the land and during the war, they are prosperous, quite prosperous. Indeed, the High plains enjoyed a period of bliss, where money was bountiful. However, when the drought extends over years and the winds arrive, the "Black Blizzards" take a hold of the sky and land. Giant masses of dirt rise and move along the High Plains buryng homes and farms, making people sick with "Dust Pnemonia, killing people and cattle and destroying the economy in one fell swoop. This lasts for almost a whole decade, from 1930 to 1940. The Dust Bowl, as this tragic event came to be called, marked the land in ways unmatched by any other disaster.<br /><br />"Dust is killing us all! God help us."<br /><br />WOW, WOW, WOW!!!!! This book is, hands down, among the best non-fiction works I have read thus far. Its equal parts fascinating and terryfying and should be taken as a cautionary tale. Timothy Egan has crafted a work that is compelling, well-researched, heart-pounding, and thorough. Following several families' personal accounts of living through the Dust Bowl, Egan constructs a comprehensive narrative. The plains were originally lived in and run by the native indians but sadly (and not surprisingly) they were ran off by the white man. Government encourage the settlement and farming of the High Plains despite the fact that the land was drought prone and received little water during its best times. During the war, wheat production spiked to high levels and farmers were making off quite well during these time. To meet demand, more land was plowed to plant more wheat. This over-plowing came to haunt the people living on the plains. The topsoil eroded and when the winds and drought came, there was no anchor to hold dirt down. Thus, the Dust Bowl began. Misguided agricultural practices made a natural disaster worse as man, to a large degree, was working against nature. It could be said that the Dust Bowl was a by-prodcut of ignorance on a grand scale.<br /><br />Without a doubt, this is a book that is going to stick with me for a while. Egan telling the story and progression of the Dust Bowl through the eyes of familes that went through it, is a great premise. The execution is superb and on point. This is a work of non-fiction that reads like fiction. The way in which he brought together the personal stories with statistics, history and goverment involvement was masterfully done. My school days are well behind me but I cannot recall learning about the Dust Bowl at all (and I took AP US History in highschool). It is estimated that the Dust Bowl damaged one hundred million acres. In addition to land loss, there was static electricity (created by the dust storms), Dust pneumonia (which killed quite number of babies, children, and senior citizens), dead cattle and at one point, swarms of locusts. Dust was everywhere, as if it had a predatory manner that would not relent. Also the Dust Bowl was compunded with the Great Depression. And yet, Egan shows how hope and optimism still existed among the plains' people. In fact, only about quarter of the overall population decided to leave during the Dirty Thirties (another name for the Dust Bowl). This has certainly been an enlightening read and helps me put things into perspective during these unpredictable times. One hundred percent recommned this book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16988560157866833959" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


