<div id="review_241948494" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/241948494" />
    <a title="Brian" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1938805-brian"><img alt="Brian" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442608867p2/1938805.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/241948494?book_show_action=true">Dec 01, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Brian" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Brian" href="/user/show/1938805-brian">Brian</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer241948494" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10132787459250424519">It is an impossibility to empathize with the tens of thousands of people that lived through the &quot;Dirty Thirties&quot; in America&apos;s prairie-land. I remember statistics from junior high civics class about the extent of the damage done to countless millions of acres in the heart of the country, I even remember a picture or two from a textbook, but nothing made the story more real than Egan&apos;s thoughtful and insightful book.<br/><br/>Rather than focus on a rehashed telling of the Dust Bowl, Egan meticulously resear</span>
  <span id="freeText10132787459250424519" style="display:none">It is an impossibility to empathize with the tens of thousands of people that lived through the "Dirty Thirties" in America's prairie-land. I remember statistics from junior high civics class about the extent of the damage done to countless millions of acres in the heart of the country, I even remember a picture or two from a textbook, but nothing made the story more real than Egan's thoughtful and insightful book.<br /><br />Rather than focus on a rehashed telling of the Dust Bowl, Egan meticulously researched first hand stories (including interviews with a couple of survivors still alive in the millennium) that made the pictures and stats come alive. The reader is taken on the ride to the "promise land" of homesteading in the early 1900's - where the hope of subsistence living and a patch of the American dream was very real for countless immigrants and poor from other parts of the nation. From the first planting to the wholesale destruction of the rich grassland to plant as much wheat as they could (to fuel the soldiers of WWI), the story-line plays out like a horror movie in slow motion. You just know what is being done to the land is going to come at a price (sound familiar?) - the surprise is that the reality was so much worse than anyone could even imagine, and that the story indeed DID turn into a horror script. A black and purple cloud 20,000 feet high and 100 miles wide barreling down the panhandle at 60-80 mph sounds like science fiction. But it was real. And it killed, over and over - for a stretch of 5 years, with little hope and nothing to do to stop it.<br /><br />Following these four or five families' stories, with their decision whether to stay or to leave the horror, burying their family, eeking out a miserable existence - is worth the time invested in this book. Just put a happy book in your reading on-deck circle and thank your lucky stars you weren't an Oakie in the '30s.....</span>
  <a data-text-id="10132787459250424519" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


